{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a58f3db5-f7a9-430d-8d5a-60b898817a65","content":"## Using MCP Inspector with a C# stdio Server\n\nRun the inspector with `npx`:\n\n```bash\nnpx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector dotnet run --project ./path/to/YourServer.csproj\n```\n\nThis launches a web UI (typically at `http://localhost:5173`) that proxies to your server over stdio.\n\n**Key steps in the Inspector UI:**\n\n1. **Connect** — Click \"Connect\" to initialize the MCP handshake.\n2. **List Tools** — Go to the \"Tools\" tab and click \"List Tools\" to verify your tools are discovered.\n3. **Call a Tool** — Select a tool, fill in the JSON arguments, and click \"Run\" to see the response.\n\n**Tips:**\n\n- Make sure your server writes MCP JSON-RPC messages to **stdout** and logs/diagnostics to **stderr** — anything non-protocol on stdout will break the connection.\n- Pass extra args after `--`: `npx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector dotnet run --project ./src/MyServer -- --my-flag`\n- Use the \"Notifications\" panel to watch `log` messages your server emits.\n- If your server is already built, point at the DLL directly: `npx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector dotnet exec ./bin/Debug/net8.0/MyServer.dll`","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"cf82ed54-c8c6-48a6-9114-fefc56de5aea","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to use the MCP Inspector to interactively test and debug their C# MCP server that uses stdio transport. This is a knowledge/guidance question, not a code change request. I can answer this directly.","outputTokens":378},"id":"fadbe0ed-8375-44e0-afdb-e2a397f50ff7","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:53:58.161Z","parentId":"e5838116-76f3-4556-9bfa-47d40485f0a6"}
